Pros/cons of each, average prices for each based on location, etc. This is def something i’ve been thinking about lately and this project is only adding to the anxiety :slightly_smiling_face:

can someone give me like a super dumbed down version of what care@work is? is it like a benefit package that employers would provide? and then the offering is basically the same as <http://regularecare.com|regularecare.com>?

care at work i think is them putting caregivers into work places
and yea then the business offers it to employers
not sure exactly how they package it
ah gotcha, so like in-house care teams
or access to backupcare or partner daycares i think
less on-site - because that gets into insurance liability i bet
have we explored what are the factors that lead to the right match (other than gut) ?
it seems like that nut has not been cracked
i don't think in depth, gut was the biggest in the research, but i'm not sure we've heard from care what they think are the factors that make the right match through their product

yeah i think education/content around what makes a good match would be super valuable — and to james’s point I think that changes a ton based on context and age. I am also interested in knowing what drives the app matching other than location/availability.
looks like james was right on care@work gets you care in home or in center, but neither of those sound like they are at the work physical location
having a hard time really differentiating <http://care.com|care.com> and care@work
maybe that's really the only diff
yeah it doesnt actually seem that different at all, but they are treating it differently. the only thing that should change for the user is the price?
i mean the process of getting the caregiver is quite different
but it seems a lot better
It changes the legitimacy of the service for the consumer
Cause the brand gets to ride the employer
FYI I'm working on a glossary of terms that I'll share after today in whatever state I can get it to, then we can all add as we learn more
i'm stuck on the fact that we need to make a great match.  beyond the match too - but we HAVE to be better than craigslist
that says HOW LITTLE PEOPLE TRUST THEM
